      "FacilityID": 22231,
      "SummaryText": "Mt. Vernon Water Treatment Plant operates 24 hrs. a day serving most of Rockcastle County. The plant is classified as a 4-A plant, with four certified operators. The plant disinfects with chlorine about 2 MGD from Lake Liniville , average dose of chlorine 100 lbs per day. The chlorine is used to kill any algae,bacteria,and pathogenes that may be present. The water plant stores about 8000 lbs of chlorine in the chlorine building that sets aside from the main operation building.The chlorine is packaged in one ton-cylinders. The facility also has a set of scale that measures the amount of chlorine beening feed per day. There are two cylinders that sets upon the scales,only one is in use, but the other is on standby. The two cylinders are link together with a automatic vacuum switch, an manul shutoff valves. The gas line running from the cylinders goes through the floor outside throuth the main building, downstairs to the injector room. This injector room is were the operators adjust the lbs used per day . The facility has in use :alarms, detectors, vents, ammonia, scba,and a look through window before entery.\nThis R M P  has two chlorine release scenerio's worst case, alternative case. The worst case is defined as the owner or operator shall  asume that the maxium quantity is released as a gas over a 10 min. due to a unspecified failure.The alternative scenerio is defined as more likely to occur.\nThe modeling was used from the EPA's RMP*COMP(TM) for both scenerios. The worst case at the plant involves  a gas release of 440 lbs min, within 10minutes. THe end point is 1.9 miles with a estimated population of 2300 residents. Only the population within the plum extending downwind of the release point is potenally affected. The meteorological conditions, namely stability F, wind speed of 1.5 m/sec 77degrees and a average humidity. The alternative scenerio involves a pipe leak , the amount of chlorine released 500lbs within a 10 minutes period, with a end point of .3 a"
